New Hope in India
Cambridge, USA — India's latest election may be the most significant positive economic event since 2014.
Indian voters decisively rejected the Congress Party, which has almost always ruled India since its independence from British rule in 1947.
They may feel pleased with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of Congress Party leader and former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, has been acting as the de facto leader since 1998, while Prime Minister Singh has been little more than a figurehead.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued populist agendas and increased transfer payments, leading to India's annual GDP growth rate falling below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP still hovers around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi promised during the campaign to bring rapid growth in employment and income across India, just as he did when serving as Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat became a business-friendly state, with economic activities expanding and attracting business investments from both within and outside India.
One important feature of the latest election was that Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the Lok Sabha, which can be considered an unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative agenda.
Two key officials will support Modi in economic planning.
The newly appointed Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has extensive political experience and previously held ministerial positions in the previous BJP government.
Arun Jaitley is also renowned as a strategic thinker who is sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan will continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan is an outstanding economist, and during his tenure as Governor, he demonstrated a desire to reduce India's high double-digit annual inflation rate and attempted to address some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
The measures required to stimulate economic growth take time to be implemented and yield results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Although India has world-class higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of the population can access the opportunities they provide, as primary and secondary education in India is significantly underdeveloped.
Only 60% of Indian adults have literacy skills at the primary school level.
Teachers themselves have low educational attainment and lack motivation, with many never even appearing at their schools.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport goods across the country and around the world.
Recent expansion of private air routes and airports indicates that private enterprises can also play a role in this sector.
Fiscal integration.
Large budget deficits are absorbing national savings that could otherwise be used to expand commercial investment. Budget deficits have led to an increase in national debt that can only be financed through future taxation.
Privatization.
The manufacturing and other industrial enterprises under the Indian government operate inefficiently, often resulting in the consumption of national savings.
Selling these enterprises directly helps accelerate economic growth.
Elimination of subsidies.
Electricity and energy subsidies have led to wasteful over-consumption and an increase in fiscal deficits.
Although these subsidies are politically difficult to eliminate, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, India's cash transfer system is efficient due to the implementation of a notable fingerprint-based cash transfer program.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
As a result, a large amount of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives are misdirected.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and regional zoning.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other major Indian cities, you will see that regional zoning restrictions lead to poor urban land use, constraining the initial dilution.
Unclear property rights, particularly agricultural land rights, have hindered industrialization in rural areas.
Relax foreign investment restrictions.
Currently, foreign enterprises cannot be majority shareholders in banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions could strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax reform.
India's complex central and state sales tax system distorts domestic trade.
The debate over replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a division of tax revenue has been ongoing for a long time, and it is now time to move to the implementation stage.
Corruption.
High-level corruption cases have undermined economic confidence and hindered officials' decision-making.
India is also deeply affected by petty corruption, and bribery has become a common feature in all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption and curb petty corruption through a new cash transfer system.
Driven by stronger growth and expectations of increased profits, India's stock market has risen by 20% this year.
Now, Modi and the BJP need to prove to the world that they can fulfill their campaign promises.
